════════════════ docs/About.md ════════════════
> [!important] Akshi is local-first software you build by describing it — apps as data, not code, that run on your devices and answer only to your keys.
## The Problem
Software is built for averages. The app you actually need, a tracker for your practice, a dashboard for your clients, an automation for your week, never quite exists. AI app builders now generate code on demand, but the result is a screen in someone's cloud: one platform, no memory of you, dead within a month. You still own nothing.
## What Akshi Does
You describe what you need in plain language and get a working app: on your Mac, PC, phone, or browser as a visual app, as a conversation when typing is easier, as a teammate your other AIs can call, or as a quiet worker running on a schedule while your devices sleep. No code is generated; there is nothing to deploy.
Underneath sits your memory vault: a private, end-to-end-encrypted store of what your apps know about you. Every app you use deepens it. Every model or agent you authorize can draw on it. Only you hold the key.
## The First App: Buddhi
Akshi is the substrate; **Buddhi** is the first app built on it — the private assistant for your **personal context**. It remembers what you work on (notes, meetings, and, as it grows, your screen context), and lets you recall it, reflect on it, and act on it. "Context" is generic: your **work** (what you were doing, what you decided), your **reflection** (habits, identity, the path you're on), and in time your **learning** are subtypes of the same memory, not separate apps.
What makes Buddhi different from the assistants that read your screen and bank your work in their cloud is not the features — it is the handling. Capture and understanding happen on your device; the memory is end-to-end-encrypted under your key; nothing it observes can be sent anywhere or acted on without your say-so. Same recall, except it physically can't leave your device, and no app can exfiltrate it. The names are the architecture: Akshi (अक्षि, _the eye_) perceives; Buddhi (बुद्धि, _the intellect_) understands what's perceived.
## What We Believe
**Yours.** Your apps and your data belong to you, not to a model vendor. Everything is exportable, and the vault is encrypted with a key we never see.
**Private by architecture.** Promises leak; encryption doesn't. We cannot read your data even if asked, which is why an ad or data business is structurally impossible for us.
**Compounding.** An app you abandon in a week is a toy. Apps wired into your memory get more useful every week you stay. That is the product, and it's also why leaving is always free: what keeps you is value, not lock-in.
**An app is not a screen.** An app is something that works for you. Screens, chat, and voice are just ways to reach it; new ways of interacting plug in without rebuilding anything, and your apps speak the open agent protocols, so they work with Claude, ChatGPT, and whatever comes next.
**Awake when you're not.** Real tools shouldn't stop when you close the laptop. Apps run on schedules across your enrolled devices, under standing permissions you set while present and can revoke any time; unattended cloud execution follows, on the same terms, as soon as we can deliver it without holding your key.
## Who It's for
People who feel the gap between "I wish an app did X" and the cost of getting one. First: independent consultants and solo professionals who handle client-sensitive work across devices. Next: small teams replacing duct-taped internal tools.
## What It's NOT
Not a code generator or cloud IDE. Not a chat assistant with plugins. Not a notes app: the vault remembers so your apps don't ask twice; you never file anything. Not open source.
---
_Akshi is where your apps, your memory, and your AI live together: built by describing, owned by you, growing more yours every day._
════════════════ docs/Beachhead.md ════════════════
The first market, the people in it, how to reach them, and the interview program that confirms or reopens the choice. The persona decision and its rationale live in Decisions (D-14); the sizing lives in Market (section 2). This note is operational. Written June 6, 2026.
## 1. Who, Precisely
Independent consultants and solo professionals who handle client-sensitive work across devices: fractional executives (CFO/CMO/COO-for-hire), operations and strategy consultants, boutique advisors, executive coaches, and the premium sub-segment of regulated solo practitioners (therapists, solo lawyers, financial advisors). The qualifying traits, all four required for "primary": earns from their own practice (not an agency employee), handles information a client would object to seeing in a third-party cloud, works across at least two devices daily, and already pays for at least one prosumer tool (Notion, Raycast, Obsidian, Calendly tier, or similar).
What they duct-tape today: client trackers in spreadsheets, engagement dashboards assembled by hand, invoice chasing by memory, intake forms in Google Forms feeding nothing, meeting-prep rituals rebuilt per client.
## 2. Where to Find Them
- **Fractionals United**: ~8,000-member community of fractional executives (Slack + directory + events; paid membership, ~$10/month), the densest single pool of the exact persona ([community](https://www.fractionalsunited.com/)).
- **Business Strategy Group**: ~8,000-member Slack for strategy and consulting professionals ([directory listing](https://slofile.com/category/Business)).
- Freelancer and agency-owner Slack/Discord communities (secondary pools; quality varies).
- LinkedIn: direct outreach to people whose headline says "fractional" or "independent consultant," warmed by the build-in-public content stream rather than cold.
- Referrals: every interview ends with "who else runs their practice like this?", the network-density bet paying for itself.
Community etiquette rule: contribute before recruiting; in paid communities, the membership fee is the cost of honest access, and recruiting posts follow each community's stated norms or go through DMs.
## 3. The Validation Wave (weeks 1-4)
_Re-sequenced per [D-55](decisions/D-55-founder-first-sequencing.md): the founder dogfoods the first AppPacks first (the founder is the D-14 wedge — sensitivity-heavy, AI-native, cross-device), then this wave is re-pointed at the founder's warm network (architects, ex-colleagues, founder peers) to test whether usage generalizes — rather than a cold wave run first. The interview shape below stands; its sequencing and recruiting source change._
Twenty to thirty conversations: roughly fifteen primary-persona, five regulated professionals, five cross-platform power users (the two adjacents from D-14). Goal is not validation theater; it is deciding whether the wedge survives contact. The persona locks or D-14 reopens at the week-4 gate.
**The ask and the value exchange.** These are people who bill by the hour, so the ask respects time: 20 minutes, scheduled, with a one-line credible reason ("I'm building tools for independent consultants and need to understand how you actually run your practice"). Primary incentive is professional reciprocity, not gift cards: a summary of anonymized findings ("what 30 consultants' tool stacks look like") and priority access to the private alpha, both offered only at the end of the call so access-seeking can't color the answers. Cash or gift-card equivalent (~$50) is held in reserve for segments where reciprocity doesn't land. Evidence: incentives lift participation 8-10 points and cut no-shows from 20-25% to 5-10%; senior professionals respond to time-respect and reciprocity over cash ([incentive data](https://greatquestion.co/blog/the-complete-guide-to-research-incentives), [B2B recruiting](https://www.userinterviews.com/blog/better-b2b-research-recruitment)).
**Interview discipline (the "Mom Test" rules, from Rob Fitzpatrick's book of that name):** talk about their life, never the idea; ask about specific past behavior, never hypothetical futures ("walk me through the last time..." not "would you use..."); compliments are deflections, not data; current spend is the only believable willingness-to-pay signal; do not pitch, do not demo in discovery interviews.
## 4. The Guide
Built to fit the 20-minute ask; if time runs short, the duct-tape inventory (questions 3-6) is the non-negotiable core and everything else yields. The privacy probe (questions 7-8) is the differentiator-test, not an afterthought: for sensitivity-heavy sub-segments (fractional finance, regulated practitioners) it joins the non-negotiable core, because a consultant with zero confidentiality hesitation is a disconfirming signal, not a neutral one (§5).
Opening (context, 5 minutes):
1. Walk me through your practice: clients, deliverables, a normal week.
2. Which devices do you touch for work in a normal day, and for what? (Probe the friction directly: walk me through the last time you needed work information on a different device than where it lived.)
The duct-tape inventory (15 minutes, the core): 3. Show or describe the tools you use to run the practice (not deliver the work): tracking clients, hours, invoices, follow-ups, prep. 4. What's the most annoying recurring task in running the practice? Walk me through the last time you did it. 5. Have you ever built or customized something yourself (spreadsheet, Notion setup, Zapier flow, Shortcuts)? What happened to it: still alive, or abandoned, and why? 6. What do you currently pay for, tool-wise? What did you cancel in the last year, and why?
The privacy probe (5 minutes): 7. Where does client-confidential information live today? Has a client ever asked, or have you ever hesitated, about a tool because of confidentiality? 8. Do you use AI tools in the practice? For what, and is there anything you deliberately keep out of them?
The automation probe (5 minutes): 9. What happens in your practice on a schedule (weekly reports, invoice runs, check-ins)? Who or what does it today? 10. Tell me about the last time something fell through the cracks because no tool was watching it.
Close: 11. If you could wave a wand and have one tool that doesn't exist, what is it? (Recorded as color, never as a roadmap; code the answer's SHAPE, not its content: a practice-running wand confirms, a delivery-work wand disconfirms per §5.) 12. Who else do you know who runs their practice like this?
## 5. What Confirms, what Disconfirms
**Confirming signals:** a graveyard of self-built tools (proves the appetite and the abandonment pain); current spend of $20+/month on practice tools; an unprompted confidentiality story; a scheduled task currently done by hand; a wand answer that matches a v1 archetype (tracker, dashboard, digest, automation).
**Disconfirming signals, taken seriously:** practices run contentedly on one spreadsheet (no tool appetite); zero confidentiality hesitation about cloud AI (kills the differentiator); wand answers that are all delivery-work, not practice-running (wrong product shape); no willingness to pay evidenced by current spend.
**Week-4 gate (defined in Playbook, Gate A):** the persona locks if a majority of primary interviews show three or more confirming signals and referrals are flowing (evidence the network is dense). It reopens D-14 if disconfirming signals dominate or if either adjacent segment shows materially stronger pull.
## 6. From Interviews to Design Partners
The fifteen to twenty-five design partners for the private alpha (Playbook, Phase B) come from this wave and its referrals: invite the interviewees whose duct-tape inventory matched the v1 archetypes, gate access on a commitment (a scheduled onboarding call and an agreement to weekly feedback), and start founder-rate billing ($10/month) in October. No public waitlist; commitment is the filter.
## 7. Logistics from India
The founder operates from India (IST, UTC+5:30); the beachhead is US-centric. Interview windows: IST evenings hit US East mornings (7-10 pm IST = 9:30 am-12:30 pm ET), the workable daily band; US West requires IST late nights (9:30 pm IST = 9 am PT), capped at two per week for sustainability. Recording with consent plus transcript notes, since back-to-back late calls degrade note quality. Async fallback: five-question Loom exchanges for participants who won't schedule, used for recruiting warmth, never counted as discovery interviews.
## 8. Where Findings Land
Interview notes are summarized per conversation into a running findings log; patterns promote into this note (persona refinements), into Market (evidence changes), or into a D-14 reopen (wedge change). Authentic voice-of-customer phrasing is harvested for About and launch copy: the category language consultants actually use replaces invented terms wherever they conflict, including the one-liner's anchor (now local-first + "apps as data, not code", having retired the coined "personal software platform" on 2026 category-design evidence) if interviews surface better words.
════════════════ docs/Market.md ════════════════
Evidence document. Numbers carry citations; claims that failed verification are marked. Last researched June 6, 2026; portable-memory addendum 2026-06-13 (§3 platforms, §4 moats).
## 1. Category and Timing
The AI app-builder category is enormous and validated: Lovable reached $400M ARR in 14 months (as of February 2026, the last public figure) at a $6.6B valuation; Replit is valued at $9B on ~$150M ARR; Cursor passed $2B in annualized revenue by early 2026 and was in funding talks at a $50B valuation by April; Bolt hit $40M ARR in its first half-year ([TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2025/12/18/vibe-coding-startup-lovable-raises-330m-at-a-6-6b-valuation/), [funding data](https://techfundingnews.com/replit-raises-400m-9b-valuation-ai-app-building/)). The honest frame: demand is proven at multi-hundred-million ARR scale, and the category's weakness is not demand but retention (section 5).
Inside this category, personal software is the unoccupied position. Every funded player builds cloud web apps for builders and developers. The only direct personal-software entrant, Raycast's Glaze, is three months into an invite-gated, Mac-only private beta with an empty store ([Glaze status](https://nativeai.agency/hub/tools/glaze/), [glaze.app](https://www.glaze.app/)). Ink & Switch's malleable-software research community has described this gap for years; no funded company executes it cross-platform and local-first ([Ink & Switch](https://www.inkandswitch.com/essay/malleable-software/)).
Timing rests on four verified shifts: open agent protocols matured under neutral governance (the Model Context Protocol at 97M monthly SDK downloads; the A2A agent-to-agent protocol at v1.0 in production; see Protocol); on-device models became good enough for private routine work on consumer hardware; inference cost fell roughly 280x in four years ([Epoch AI](https://epoch.ai/data-insights/llm-inference-price-trends)); and consumer trust in cloud AI measurably cracked: 81% of consumers are concerned about AI accessing their private data, only 5% of Americans deeply trust AI, and comfort with autonomous AI agents fell from 70% to 45% in one year ([Relyance](https://www.relyance.ai/consumer-ai-trust-survey-2025), [YouGov](https://yougov.com/en-us/articles/53701-most-americans-use-ai-but-still-dont-trust-it), [2026 survey](https://www.androidheadlines.com/2026/03/ai-consumer-usage-survey-2026-control-trust.html)).
## 2. The Beachhead, Sized Bottom-up
Primary wedge: independent consultants and solo professionals handling client-sensitive work.
- 7.3M Americans work full-time as independent consultants; 5.6M independents earn $100K+ ([MBO Partners via consulting statistics](https://www.melisaliberman.com/blog/consulting-statistics)).
- The broader US freelance population is 64-76M, contributing $1.27T, with ~30M in knowledge services ([Upwork](https://www.upwork.com/resources/freelancing-stats), [stats roundup](https://high5test.com/freelance-statistics/)).
- Street math: 5.6M high-earning independents x $192/year (Plus tier at monthly billing; annual billing is $160) = $1.1B serviceable US wedge before teams, before global. Gate D ($10-20K MRR) requires roughly 700-1,300 subscribers, or 0.02% of that population.
Why this wedge: concrete recurring tool needs (client trackers, engagement dashboards, billing automations), structural privacy requirement (client confidentiality makes cloud builders unusable for much of their work), cross-device workdays, network density (communities and referrals), and willingness to pay demonstrated by existing prosumer spend. Expansion: small teams replacing duct-taped internal tools, anchored by the multi-billion internal-tooling market (Retool-scale).
## 3. Competitive Map
Three rings, one structural claim.
**Direct (personal software):** Glaze. Mac-only, waitlisted, credit-priced, closed store, Raycast distribution. Validates demand; does not contest cross-platform, server execution, or data ownership.
**Adjacent (AI app builders):** Lovable, Bolt, v0, Replit, Firebase Studio. Cloud web-app factories for a builder audience. They generate code the user must host and maintain; apps are public-web-shaped, wrong for confidential client work. Their iOS paths route through compiled exports or web delivery; their economics are credit-metered cloud inference.
**DIY (the unpriced competitor):** the self-hosted stack. A technically capable consultant can run a local memory layer (Mem0, Obsidian-plus-adapter) connected to Claude or ChatGPT via the Model Context Protocol today, getting much of the privacy story at zero subscription. Akshi's honest edge over this path is not privacy (both are local): it is the generation loop, the cross-platform shell, and zero-ops UX. Gate B should include design partners drawn from people who already run local AI tools, since they are the hardest sell.
**Platforms (the real long-term competitors):** ChatGPT Apps, Claude Cowork, Google AI Studio app generation, and Apple's evolving on-device AI stack. They own distribution to billions. The structural claim, stated carefully: their business models require holding user data and locking memory to their assistant; user-owned, model-portable, end-to-end-encrypted memory is the one feature set they are economically punished for copying. The caveat that survives alongside this claim: nothing in the evidence says they move slowly. The first week of June 2026 alone produced three acceleration signals: Apple approved the first third-party AI agent (Poke) on Messages for Business ([TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/06/04/apple-approves-poke-as-the-first-ai-agent-on-its-messages-for-business-platform/)), Google partnered with MWM AI on a mobile app-creation agent team aimed at 500M creators ([announcement](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/mwm-ai-partners-with-google-cloud-to-launch-new-mobile-agents-for-app-creators-and-entrepreneurs-302790646.html)), and Google shipped Gemini Spark, a 24/7 cloud-resident personal agent executing tasks in third-party apps ([TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/19/google-introduces-gemini-spark-a-24-7-agentic-assistant-with-gmail-integration/)). One nuance the structural claim must carry: Apple is the partial exception, since its business model sells hardware rather than holding data, which makes it the likeliest platform to ship credible user-owned memory; Vision's falsification clause names exactly that event.
_2026-06-13 update (deep-research-verified, [moat-verification](research/2026-06-13-moat-verification.md)):_ the structural claim **survives primary-source verification**, with one competitive-map addition. Owned + portable + E2EE + provenance-typed memory is NOT commoditizing — every signal covers only a subset of the four axes: **Mem0** (the one verified-traction player — $24M Series A, 41K stars, 186M Q3 API calls) is developer agent-memory infra with no E2EE/ownership/provenance (the crowded adjacent space, not Akshi's axes); **Anuma** is refuted on traction (~$1K ARR, 1 customer; "60K users" unaudited PR) and on-chain not local-first; **PAM** ([arXiv 2605.11032](https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.11032)) is a single-author preprint, not E2EE, zero adoption; **Gemini import** is one-shot lossy non-E2EE — which SUPPORTS the thesis; **Apple WWDC 2026** is "borrow the model, cage the data" — Apple-controlled, not user-owned. No verified player combines more than two axes with traction. The real correction is a new entrant in the **Direct** ring: **Epicenter** (YC S25, ~$1M, 4K+ stars, shipping) builds open-source local-first apps sharing one user-owned store (plain-text + SQLite + CRDT) — a real occupant of the broad apps-on-owned-memory slot, though its apps are conventional code (not signed non-Turing DATA manifests) and its store is not E2EE-at-rest or provenance-typed. And **Microsoft 365 Copilot declarative agents** are a shipped apps-as-DATA platform (JSON/TypeSpec manifests) but tenant-bound, server-side — the MCPTox-vulnerable agentic-loop model §7.3 forecloses, not user-owned memory. Net: the moat claim holds as scoped; §1's "unoccupied position" line is qualified to "apps-as-signed-DATA on an E2EE provenance-typed owned vault is unoccupied; the broader apps-on-owned-memory slot is contested by Epicenter."
_2026-06-18 — Little Bird, the closest comp to the keystone app ([[D-73 Buddhi keystone + two-brand]]):_ **Little Bird** (littlebird.ai, $11M seed Mar 2026, led by Lotus Studio + A-list angels) is a Mac-native personal-context assistant that reads structured screen content continuously + transcribes meetings, stores the context as text **on AWS**, and answers/acts across apps; it reports 84% of users saving ≥half a day/week ([TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/03/23/littlebird-raises-11m-to-capture-context-from-your-computer-so-you-can-query-your-data/), [PRNewswire](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/littlebird-raises-11-million-to-launch-the-only-ai-that-already-knows-what-youre-working-on-302721664.html)). It is the strongest funded **validation of the work-context-recall subtype's demand** — and it occupies only a subset of the moat axes: privacy is by policy (server-readable AWS plaintext, no user-held keys), with no ownership / portability / provenance typing, and its execution is the agentic-loop model §7.3 forecloses (the MCPTox surface). So it confirms the wedge without contesting the moat: Buddhi is the same value handled by architecture (on-device, E2EE, provenance-typed, declarative), which Little Bird is structurally unable to copy without abandoning its cloud model. Belongs in the Direct ring as a near-neighbor (personal-software recall), distinct from Glaze (app-builder) and Epicenter (apps-on-owned-store).
## 4. Moats: what Akshi Has, what it Must Earn
Method note: every claim below was stress-tested by deliberately sourcing the strongest counter-evidence available (June 2026); where the counter-evidence won, the claim was demoted. The tiers reflect those verdicts.
**Real today, time-limited: local-first margins.** AI-native products average 52% gross margins versus 75-85% for SaaS; inference consumes ~23% of revenue at scaling companies; Cursor ran negative gross margins until April 2026 ([ICONIQ via TechTimes](https://www.techtimes.com/articles/317542/20260601/ai-agent-economics-token-tax-locks-gross-margins-30-points-below-saas-baseline.htm)). Routing routine inference to user devices removes that tax. Cloud costs fall 60-70% yearly, so treat this as a 2-3 year cost advantage that is durable only where cloud is architecturally excluded: private data, which is the beachhead's defining workload.
**The central hypothesis, not yet a moat: the compounding vault.** The bet is that apps wired into accumulated personal memory escape the category's abandonment pattern. Counter-evidence is taken seriously: ChatGPT ships memory at scale and still churns ~19% monthly on free tier ([retention analysis](https://www.arcade.dev/blog/user-retention-in-ai-platforms-metrics/)), and 573+ MCP memory servers are commoditizing memory as infrastructure ([PulseMCP](https://www.pulsemcp.com/servers?q=memory)). Akshi additionally promises full export, deliberately zeroing exit costs, so retention must come from compounding value, not friction. Investors fund the thesis (Mem0's $24M Series A is built on it: [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/28/mem0-raises-24m-from-yc-peak-xv-and-basis-set-to-build-the-memory-layer-for-ai-apps/)); nobody has proven it with retention data. Gate B (defined in Playbook) exists to prove or kill it.
_2026-06-13 verification (deep research, [moat-verification](research/2026-06-13-moat-verification.md)) — a same-day scan had demoted this tier on a "memory is commoditizing" claim that FAILED verification; the demotion is withdrawn._ The owned + portable + E2EE + provenance-typed conjunction did NOT commoditize — no verified player ships more than two of the four axes (Mem0 = funded agent-memory infra without E2EE/ownership; Anuma = ~$1K-ARR, refuted; PAM = preprint; Gemini import = lossy, supports the thesis; Apple = caged-not-owned). So this tier stands as written. The genuine update is competitive (§3): **Epicenter (YC S25)** now occupies the broad apps-on-owned-memory slot, so the still-unoccupied carve-out is the narrower apps-as-signed-DATA + E2EE + provenance-typed vault — which keeps the central hypothesis (compounding apps stick) the load-bearing unproven bet, tested at Gate B. The strategic consequence is unchanged regardless: the moat converts only via Gate-B retention evidence, not via racing the adjacent memory-infra layer.
**Earned later: marketplace network effects.** The mechanic is real at critical mass: Notion's 1.5M monthly template downloads drive acquisition; Obsidian sustains 6M users and 1,400 plugins against Notion's 100M ([Notion data](https://fueler.io/blog/notion-usage-revenue-valuation-growth-statistics), [comparison](https://tech-insider.org/obsidian-vs-notion-2026/)). The failure mode is documented too: OpenAI's Plugin Store collapsed under spam and was shut down in April 2024. Worth zero until Akshi has users and curation.
**Reclassified, not moats:** protocol-native positioning is distribution (protocol-era winners owned the domain complexity behind the protocol, never the protocol surface: [Leonis Capital](https://www.leoniscap.com/research/mcps-value-creation-capture-and-destruction-lessons-from-the-api-era)); per-domain distillation is a cost lever, not defensibility (data-moat value asymptotes: [a16z](https://a16z.com/the-empty-promise-of-data-moats/)); and declarative architecture is justified on permanent grounds (security sandbox, instant generation, cross-interface identity, safe template sharing) with store compliance as a consequence, not a cause. Store policies are temporary and routable: direct desktop distribution, web delivery, EU alternative stores, and policy shifts (Replit renegotiated its way back into App Store updates in May 2026: [AppleInsider](https://appleinsider.com/articles/26/05/15/apples-treatment-of-ai-coding-apps-could-be-shifting-with-replit-update)) all exist as paths.
**Stated plainly:** pre-PMF companies do not have moats; they have advantages and a plan to convert them. Akshi's conversion plan is the playbook's gates.
## 5. The Graveyard, Honestly
The category's retention record is the strongest argument against the company, so it gets the most prominent placement.
- Vibe-coding platforms shed 27-64% of traffic within weeks of revenue milestones; Bolt's CEO concedes churn "is really high for everyone" ([analysis](https://www.finalroundai.com/blog/vibe-coding-bubble)).
- No platform publishes day-30 survival of created apps, so Akshi's baseline is a stated proxy: general mobile-app day-30 _user_ retention runs ~7% across categories ([Adjust/AppsFlyer benchmarks](https://www.businessofapps.com/data/app-retention-rates/)), and vibe-coding platforms signal high project abandonment indirectly (Lovable and v0 traffic down 40-64% from their 2026 peaks). The north-star ≥40% is benchmarked against that proxy explicitly, and the alpha cohort produces the first true created-app survival measurement.
- AI products suffer "tourist" cohorts; the honest retention metric is rebased to month 3 (M12/M3), per a16z's benchmark work across hundreds of AI companies ([a16z](https://a16z.com/ai-retention-benchmarks/)). The more demanding comparison class for the vault thesis is daily-use tools _with_ memory: ChatGPT churns ~19% monthly on free tier with memory active, and that, not the no-code graveyard, is the benchmark the vault must ultimately beat once past Gate B.
- End-user programming has a 30-year ceiling pattern: Yahoo Pipes died, IFTTT stalled and repriced into backlash, Shortcuts remains a power-user niche. Survivors (Notion, Airtable) won by making building emergent inside a tool people already used daily, never the headline ask. Akshi's design answer: the headline ask is "describe a problem," and the vault makes daily use compound.
- Privacy positioning has a measured ceiling: Signal holds ~1.3% of WhatsApp's user base after 15 years; DuckDuckGo holds 0.86% of search ([Signal stats](https://www.businessofapps.com/data/signal-statistics/), [DDG share](https://earthweb.com/duckduckgo-market-share/)). Obsidian and Proton prove the segment supports real businesses. This is consistent with a beachhead strategy and is the named risk to the billion-scale goal in Vision, which requires ownership going mainstream, not just the privacy segment.
## 6. Pricing Landscape
Accepted prosumer anchors: Obsidian Sync $8, Raycast Pro $8, Notion $10, Granola $10, Raycast AI $20, Cursor Pro $20, Lovable Pro $25 ([pricing guide](<https://www.news.aakashg.com/p/how-to-price-ai-products>)). Akshi's $16 Plus / $28 Power sits inside the accepted band. Credit-based pricing is the category's documented sore point (Cursor's June 2025 repricing apology; Lovable complaint threads); flat tiers with invisible metering are the differentiated stance ([credit pricing flaws](<https://softwarepricing.com/blog/credit-based-pricing-ai/>)). Only 2% of sub-$25 ARPU products exceed 100% net revenue retention, which is why the team tier exists.
## 7. What Must Be True
Three falsifiable market claims, each mapped to a playbook gate. First, consultants will adopt and _keep_ generated apps at multiples of the 7% baseline (Gate B: ≥40% 30-day app survival). Second, ownership and privacy convert to payment at prosumer prices (Gate C: ≥3% free-to-paid trending to 5%). Third, individual value expands into team revenue (Gate D: team conversions and $10-20K MRR). Any of these failing falsifies the market thesis as scoped, and the documented fallbacks (vault-first pivot, distribution-first rebalance, exit) activate.
